<p><em>Indicative. Verify on the live pricing page. INR-native, UPI accepted, GST invoice with input credit.</em></p>

<h2>Best Indian use cases</h2>

<h3>Indian D2C brands</h3>
<p>Cart-abandonment with one-click recovery inside email, product reviews inline, NPS surveys, festival campaigns with calendar booking. The AMP advantage is biggest where customer friction kills conversion.</p>

<h3>Indian SaaS marketing teams</h3>
<p>Onboarding sequences with inline product tutorials, in-email demo bookings, feature announcements with embedded feedback forms.</p>

<h3>Community and event-led businesses</h3>
<p>RSVPs, ticket purchases, polls, surveys inside email. For Indian conferences, meetups, course launches, AMP shortens the funnel materially.</p>

<h3>Indian agencies running client email programs</h3>
<p>Agency tier with multi-brand support and white-label options.</p>

<h2>Where Mailmodo is not the right tool</h2>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Pure transactional email at scale</strong>, Use SendGrid, Amazon SES, Postmark for high-volume transactional.</li>
  <li><strong>Heavy creator-led newsletter</strong>, Beehiiv or Substack remain better creator platforms.</li>
  <li><strong>Email is not your primary channel</strong>, If your funnel runs on paid ads, Instagram, or WhatsApp alone, Mailmodo is overkill.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Indian alternatives</h2>
<ul>
<li><strong>Mailchimp, Klaviyo, HubSpot</strong>, Global tools, no AMP-native depth.</li>
<li><strong>Zoho Campaigns</strong>, Cheap, Indian-built, part of Zoho ecosystem.</li>
<li><strong>Webengage</strong>, Indian engagement platform, broader scope.</li>
<li><strong>MoEngage</strong>, Indian customer engagement, more enterprise.</li>
</ul>

